nts <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bruen","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Irish: Braon, pronounced \"breen,\" a drop"],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bruen Stapleford was born in 1230, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert le Brun, was 40 and his mother, Eva Stretun, was 40. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1230–":"1230–Surnud","1230–1260":"1230–1260","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1260–1321":"1260–1321","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190–1243":"1190–1243","1190":"1190","1248":"1248","1321":"1321","1243":"1243","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230–":"1230–Kuollut","1230–1260":"1230–1260","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","1260–1321":"1260–1321","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190–1243":"1190–1243","1190":"1190","1248":"1248","1321":"1321","1243":"1243","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1230–":"1230–Décédé","1230–1260":"1230–1260","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1248–Female":"1248–Décédée","1260–1321":"1260–1321","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190–1243":"1190–1243","1190":"1190","1248":"1248","1321":"1321","1243":"1243","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert Bruen Stapleford est né en 1230, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Robert le B